message.content: Write $\frac{x}{x^{2/3}}$ as $\frac{x^{1/3}}{x^{1/3}}$, so we get: \[4x^{1/3}-2 \cdot \frac{x}{x^{2/3}}= 4x^{1/3}-2 \cdot \frac{x^{1/3}}{x^{1/3}} = 4x^{1/3}-2x^{1/3}=2x^{1/3}.\]Setting this equal to $7+\sqrt[3]{x}$, we have $2x^{1/3} = 7+\sqrt[3]{x}$. Cubing both sides to eliminate the fractional exponents gives $(2x^{1/3})^3 = (7+\sqrt[3]{x})^3$. Expanding each side using the binomial theorem gives $8x = 343 + 3\cdot 7^2 (\sqrt[3]{x}^2) + 3 \cdot 7 (\sqrt[3]{x}^3) + x$, or $7\cdot \sqrt[3]{x}^3 + 3 \cdot 7^2 (\sqrt[3]{x}^2) - 8x = 343$. We can now factor a 7 out of each term to get \[7(\sqrt[3]{x}^3 + 21 (\sqrt[3]{x}^2) - 8x) = 343.\]The terms in parentheses can then be used to substitute $y = \sqrt[3]{x}$, so we have \[7(y^{3}+21 y^2-8y^3) = 343.\]Simplifying the cube on the left and subtracting 343 gives $-y^3+21y^2-8y^3 = -7y^3+21y^2 = 0$. Factoring out $y^2$ gives $y^2(-7y+21) = 0$, so either $y^2 = 0$ or $-7y+21 = 0$. The latter gives $y = 3$. Therefore, $\sqrt[3]{x} = y = 3$, which implies $x = 3^3 = \boxed{27}$.
